T1  - Schooling, Family Background, and Adoption: Is It Nature or Is It Nurture?
AU  - Plug, Erik
AU  - Vijverberg, Wim
Y1  - 2003/06/01
PY  - 2003
DA  - 2003/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/374185
DO  - 10.1086/374185
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 611
EP  - 641
VL  - 111
IS  - 3
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - When parents are more educated, their children tend to receive more schooling as well. Does this occur because parental ability is passed on genetically or because more educated parents provide a better environment for children to flourish? Using an intergenerational sample of families, we estimate on the basis of a comparison of biological and adopted children that about 55?60 percent of the parental ability is genetically transmitted.
AB  - When parents are more educated, their children tend to receive more schooling as well. Does this occur because parental ability is passed on genetically or because more educated parents provide a better environment for children to flourish? Using an intergenerational sample of families, we estimate on the basis of a comparison of biological and adopted children that about 55?60 percent of the parental ability is genetically transmitted.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/374185
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/374185
Y2  - 2024/03/19
